SIMPLE: winder
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Winder
<hw>Wind"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Wind</er> to
turn.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, winds; hence, a creeping or
winding plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An apparatus used for winding silk, cotton, etc., on
spools, bobbins, reels, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>One in a flight of steps which
are curved in plan, so that each tread is broader at one end than at the
other; -- distinguished from <xex>flyer</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Winder
<hw>Wind"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>winder</ets> a fan, and to winnow. <?/. Cf. <er>Winnow</er>.]</ety>
<def>To fan; to clean grain with a fan.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Winder
<hw>Wind"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A blow taking away the
breath.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Winder
<hw>Wind"er</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To wither; to fail.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Windfall</ent>⟦br⟧
